Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Kaumudi Moholkar¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data has 113937 rows and 81 columns. It has majorly numeric data and a few objects. It has all the information on the loan status, employment status, loan payment information, and so on.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am focussing on predicting which type of loans are more prevalent and if any steps can be taken to improve the company's loan allotment criteria. So I will analyze the Loan Status, Employment Status, Loan Amount, Income verifiable, and so on.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Loan status, Employment status, borrower APR, Income range, Income Verifiable, Stated Monthly Income, Debt to Income Ratio, Loan Original amount.

In [12]:
#function to create category of columns
def cat_create(classes, col):
    sclasses = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = classes)
    loan_df[col] = loan_df[col].astype(sclasses)
In [13]:
#Creating a category for loan status
status_classes = ['Current', 'Completed', 'Chargedoff', 'Defaulted', 'Past Due', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Cancelled']
cat_create(status_classes, 'LoanStatus')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

For the data analyzed, the Stated monthly income has a normal distribution with a mean of 5000. Borrower APR looks multi-modal, with many small peaks and there is one peak that is largest at somewhere around 0.35. There are a few points here and there greater than 0.4 APR.

The remaining analysis was done on the categorical and boolean data. Income Verifiable, Loan Term Distribution, Occupation, Income Range, Employment status, Loan Status. There was something unusual about the debt-to-income ratio with the drastic drops at three to four points.

To convert various columns to categories a few transformations were done. Also, the handling of null values was done for the income range column.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Loan Status: A majority of the people are currently having their loans with Prosper, the next in line are people who have completed their loan and charged off. There are only a few who have their loans past due or have canceled their loans. So, it can be said that the company is handling the loans pretty well.

Employment Status: A large number of people who have loans are employed. With only a few people being part-time workers, not employed or retired. So this can ensure the possibility of people paying off the loan.

Income Verifiable: About 92.4 % percent of people have their income verified, which shows the authenticity of the people taking the loan. A data frame was created for plotting the pie chart with the labels and percentages.

Borrower APR: The distribution seems to be multimodal with many small peaks. However, there is one major peak at 0.35 APR. The data can be further analyzed to give a better understanding of the peaks.

Income Range: 'Not displayed' and 'Not employed' all need to be updated with 0 as there is no income figure. The majority of people lie in the 25,000 - 49,999 range and with a small difference a lot of people lie in the 50,000 - 74,999 range.

Occupation: A vast population of people taking loan lie in the 'other' category. So we cannot fully understand the occupation of people who are taking loans.

Stated Monthly Income: A normal distribution is observed in the stated monthly income of the people taking a loan. There is a mean of 5000, but the plot looks good and nothing unusual.

Term: The columns were changed to categorical by creating a new category class for the term. The column was updated and then the pie chart was plotted. A lot of people have a loan term of 36 months, about 77% of the people and about 21.5% of the people had a loan with 60 months term and there were only 1.4% of people with 12 months of the loan term.

Debt to Income Ratio: The distribution was plotted from 0 to 1. However, the majority of the data lies between 0 to 0.6 which is good as a lot of people have a debt-to-income ratio. However, there are some drastic drops in 3-4 different areas.

Loan Original Amount: The loan amount lies from 0 to 35,000 with big peaks in values of 5000. Assuming people tend to take the round figure and 5000 value loans as a majority.

There is a higher APR for the charged-off status across multiple employment statuses. Also, full-time employers have a higher APR range. This can mean there is no proper background check taking place before loan approvals.

People working part-time have more loans past due dates indicating they take higher loans than they can afford to pay. Also, self-employed people have default loan status for larger loan amounts, which makes both a high-risk category for future loan approval.

Conclusions¶

To summarize, it is clear that when the charged-off and default loan status categories are taken into consideration and proper vetting is done, it can help the company have more profit than loss. Also, if people cannot afford to take loans they must be continuously monitored before allocating the loans.
